adjective.description: Having all the necessary or appropriate parts.
examples: a complete list of courses offered by the college
no wardrobe is complete this year without culottes

adjective.description: (often used for emphasis) to the greatest extent or degree; total.
examples: their marriage came as a complete surprise to me
he only needed one thing to complete his happiness
more recent box cameras complete the collection

phrases: the detachable keyboard comes complete with numeric keypad
origin: Late Middle English: from Old French complet or Latin completus, past participle of complere fill up, finish, fulfill, from com- (expressing intensive force) + plere fill.
